{"title":"MicroSHIFT Sword Wide-Range Mechanical Gravel Groups Debut","link":"https://bikerumor.com/microshift-sword-gravel-bike-drivetrains/","date":1689719540000,"content":"<p>MicroSHIFT has always kinda flown under the radar with well-performing road and mountain bike groups at great prices, gliding under the shadow of SRAM and Shimano’s position as mainstream category leaders. So their new Sword gravel groups shouldn’t come as a surprise given the category’s growth, but they definitely come out swinging.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Offering dedicated 1x and 2x setups, the MicroSHIFT Sword groupsets come with shifters, derailleurs, cassette, cranks, and chainrings, leaving you to source whatever mechanical brake calipers you want to run. And yes, it’s fully mechanical and very affordable. Let’s take a look…</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Really wide gearing from just 10 speeds</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-19.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1201\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-19.jpg\" alt=\"microshift sword gravel bike being ridden\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-19.jpg 1800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-19-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-19-800x534.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-19-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-19-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-19-1536x1025.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-19-720x480.jpg 720w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>One of the biggest standouts for the group is how big of a gear range the 2x group will get you. It’s offered with two chainring combos, 46/29 and 48/31, each with a massive 17-tooth jump. Combine that with the 11-38 cassette and you can get a 24% lower gear (0.76 lowest gear ratio) than with a standard 50/34 compact chainring setup with 11-34 cassette!</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-18.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1200\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-18.jpg\" alt=\"microshift sword 1x gravel bike drivetrain\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-18.jpg 1800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-18-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-18-800x533.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-18-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-18-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-18-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-18-720x480.jpg 720w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The 1x chainring is offered with 40 and 42-tooth counts, and with the 40T paired to an 11-48 cassette, it’ll give you a 0.83 lowest gear ratio. If you can’t crawl up any climb with those, it’s not the drivetrain that’s the issue.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Shifting &amp; Ergonomics</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-11.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1200\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-11.jpg\" alt=\"microshift sword gravel group brake levers\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-11.jpg 1800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-11-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-11-800x533.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-11-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-11-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-11-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-11-720x480.jpg 720w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The Sword brake levers are designed for flared bars up to 45º, with an outward angle to match where your fingers are on modern gravel handlebars, but they say it’ll still work fine with 0º flare bars, too.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-12.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1200\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-12.jpg\" alt=\"microshift sword gravel group brake levers\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-12.jpg 1800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-12-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-12-800x533.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-12-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-12-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-12-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-12-720x480.jpg 720w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The levers have a high pivot placement to increase leverage and reduce reach, so you have maximum braking power even with a single finger, which is helpful when braking from atop the hoods. The internals pull more cable than their road levers, too, giving you more power on the rougher surfaces.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-1.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1201\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-1.jpg\" alt=\"microshift sword gravel group shifter levers\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-1.jpg 1800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-1-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-1-800x534.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-1-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-1-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-1-1536x1025.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-1-720x480.jpg 720w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The shifter buttons are two distinct buttons, with a bigger paddle for pulling cable (up to larger gears), and a release paddle to click down to a smaller gear. There’s a single right-hand shifter to handle the rear, but the left hand gets options. A matching two-trigger design handles front shifts on a 2x build, or opt for a fixed brake lever for standard 1x builds, or one with a pivoting lever to control dropper posts.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-2.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1201\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-2.jpg\" alt=\"top down view of microshift sword gravel group shifter brake lever hoods\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-2.jpg 1800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-2-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-2-800x534.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-2-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-2-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-2-1536x1025.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-2-720x480.jpg 720w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The hoods have textured rubber covers, and underneath are independent reach adjustments for shift and brake levers, so you can get everything exactly where you like it.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Shifty, Pedally Bits</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-21.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1201\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-21.jpg\" alt=\"microshift sword gravel group front derailleur cable tension adjustment\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-21.jpg 1800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-21-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-21-800x534.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-21-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-21-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-21-1536x1025.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-21-720x480.jpg 720w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The front derailleur gets a clever cable tension adjustment screw that’s easily accessible from the top. Once installed, simply turn a 3mm hex wrench in there to loosen or tighten cable tension to fine-tune your shifting.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-13.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1620\" height=\"1198\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-13.jpg\" alt=\"microshift sword gravel group derailleur comparison\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-13.jpg 1620w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-13-297x220.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-13-800x592.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-13-120x89.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-13-768x568.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-13-1536x1136.jpg 1536w\" /></a><figcaption>Long cage on the left, Medium cage on the right.</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The rear derailleur comes in two variants, one for 2x with a long cage to handle the extra chain movement, and a medium cage for 1x builds.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-8.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1620\" height=\"800\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-8.jpg\" alt=\"microshift sword gravel group rear derailleur clutch\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-8.jpg 1620w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-8-297x147.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-8-800x395.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-8-120x59.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-8-768x379.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-8-1536x759.jpg 1536w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>There’s a built-in clutch that can be turned on or off for easier wheel removal or improved chain management. The expected bezel to adjust cable tension is there, but it sits on an orbital mount that allows 15º of rotation in any direction. So, no matter what odd angle your cable housing exits your frame, the bezel’s range of motion helps improve the angle at which the housing feeds into the derailleur for less cable friction and smoother shifts.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Lastly, the pulley cage is easily removable and replaceable should you bend or break it…and it’s the only piece that needs to be changed to go from 1x to 2x and back. Well, you’ll want to swap the cassette and chainrings, but you won’t need a new derailleur or shifters to switch between drivetrain types, just change the cage.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-14.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1200\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-14.jpg\" alt=\"microshift sword gravel group crankset\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-14.jpg 1800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-14-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-14-800x533.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-14-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-14-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-14-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-14-720x480.jpg 720w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-20.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1201\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-20.jpg\" alt=\"microshift sword gravel bike double chainring\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-20.jpg 1800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-20-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-20-800x534.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-20-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-20-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-20-1536x1025.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-20-720x480.jpg 720w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The crankset is also the same for 1x and 2x, with an asymmetric 110/80 BCD that fits one or two chainrings, both theirs and many aftermarket options, too.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-15.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1200\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-15.jpg\" alt=\"microshift sword gravel group single chainring on crankset\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-15.jpg 1800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-15-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-15-800x533.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-15-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-15-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-15-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-15-720x480.jpg 720w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>It has a 24mm spindle to fit any Shimano or similar bottom bracket, and comes in 165/170/172.5/175mm lengths.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-4.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1201\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-4.jpg\" alt srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-4.jpg 1800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-4-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-4-800x534.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-4-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-4-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-4-1536x1025.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-4-720x480.jpg 720w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The 10-speed 11-38 cassettes are all new for this group, and come in two variants, both with 11-13-15-17-19-21-24-28-32-38 tooth counts. The G-Series is the higher-end, lighter version that uses an alloy carrier with alloy big cog, and the H-Series is all steel. Complete weights listed further down in the article.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-16.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1200\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-16.jpg\" alt=\"microshift advent x wide range cassette for mountain bikes and gravel\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-16.jpg 1800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-16-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-16-800x533.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-16-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-16-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-16-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microSHIFT-Sword-gravel-group-16-720x480.jpg 720w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The wider range 1x cassettes are their Advent X 10-speed mountain bike cassettes (425g for G-Series, 662g for H-series) with 11-13-15-18-21-24-28-34-40-48 cogs. All cassettes fit on a standard HG freehub body.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Parts &amp; Spec</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microshift-sword-gravel-group-parts-compatibility-diagram.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1920\" height=\"1890\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microshift-sword-gravel-group-parts-compatibility-diagram.jpg\" alt srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microshift-sword-gravel-group-parts-compatibility-diagram.jpg 1920w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microshift-sword-gravel-group-parts-compatibility-diagram-297x292.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microshift-sword-gravel-group-parts-compatibility-diagram-800x788.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microshift-sword-gravel-group-parts-compatibility-diagram-120x118.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microshift-sword-gravel-group-parts-compatibility-diagram-768x756.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microshift-sword-gravel-group-parts-compatibility-diagram-1536x1512.jpg 1536w\" /></a><figcaption>Note: The 1x dropper and standalone brake lever images are swapped, the one with the paddle is the dropper post version, and they should have “L” rather than “R” in the model name.</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Claimed weights for all components are:</p>\n\n\n\n<ul>\n<li>Shifter SB-G7000R: 256g</li>\n\n\n\n<li>Shifter SB-G7020L: 256g (2x left)</li>\n\n\n\n<li>Shifter SB-G7000L: 170g (1x left)</li>\n\n\n\n<li>Shifter SB-G7000LD: 250g (dropper left)</li>\n\n\n\n<li>Front Derailleur: 108g (braze on)</li>\n\n\n\n<li>Rear Der-Med: 308g</li>\n\n\n\n<li>Rear Der-Long: 329g</li>\n\n\n\n<li>Cassette H105 11-38: 453g (all steel cogs)</li>\n\n\n\n<li>Cassette G105 11-38: 336g (alloy spider with alloy big ring)</li>\n\n\n\n<li>Crankset 1x 40T: 790g (810g 42T)</li>\n\n\n\n<li>Crankset 2x 46/29: 925g</li>\n</ul>\n\n\n\n<p>All cranks weighed in 172.5mm length without pedal spacers. Individual component pricing is:</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microshift-sword-gravel-group-pricing-chart.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"811\" height=\"352\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microshift-sword-gravel-group-pricing-chart.jpg\" alt=\"microSHIFT Sword gravel group pricing chart\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microshift-sword-gravel-group-pricing-chart.jpg 811w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microshift-sword-gravel-group-pricing-chart-297x129.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microshift-sword-gravel-group-pricing-chart-800x347.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microshift-sword-gravel-group-pricing-chart-120x52.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/microshift-sword-gravel-group-pricing-chart-768x333.jpg 768w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>We have a group on the way (along with some TRP brakes) and will report back once we’ve put a few miles on it!</p>\n\n\n\n<p><em><a href=\"https://www.microshift.com/products/groups/sword/\" target=\"_blank\">MicroSHIFT.com</a></em></p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/microshift-sword-gravel-bike-drivetrains/\">MicroSHIFT Sword Wide-Range Mechanical Gravel Groups Debut</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://bikerumor.com\">Bikerumor</a>.</p>","author":"Tyler Benedict","siteTitle":"Bikerumor","siteHash":"49f427af0a926f4232eb837006841d7242e153e3afbb590f32e4b104ea3e2718","entryHash":"b3a27f792845fb1c1e8556b7ab28c2d4f0265c1ae355d8b71da797486c5a6dd2","category":"Cycling"}